President Muhammadu Buhari Thursday presented the 2021 budget proposal of N13.08 trillion to a joint session of the National Assembly.  Addressing the joint session of federal lawmakers before presenting the proposed 2021 budget tagged â€œThe Budget of Economic Recovery and Resilience, the President gave a breakdown of the performance of the 2020 budget admitting that revenue generation to fund annual budgets remains a major challenge being faced by his administration, thereby directing ministers to monitor strict revenue generation by the government agencies.  The President, while giving a breakdown of the 2021 budget estimates, said the budget has an aggregate revenue projection of N7.89 trillion, N484.49 billion was for statutory transfers, N5.65 trillion for non-debt recurrent expenditure and N3.85 trillion for capital expenditure, while the 2021 Budget deficit (inclusive of Government Owned Enterprises and project-tied loans), is projected at N5.20 trillion which represents 3.64 percent of estimated GDP.  President of the Senate, Ahmad Lawan and his House of Representatives Speaker, Hon. Femi Gbajabiamila, assured that the National Assembly is ready to ensure proper scrutiny of the 2021 Appropriation Bill and passage before the end of 2020.   Our Correspondent reports that the budget proposal is predicated on N379 per dollar exchange rate; oil benchmark of $40 barrel per day; and oil production volume of 1.86 million per day, while inflation growth rate was projected at 11.95 percent; and Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth rate was fixed at 3 percent.  For Sectoral Allocations, Ministry of Power is to receive N198 billion, Ministry of Defence N121 billion, Works and Housing N440 billion, Ministry of Water Resources N146 billion and Ministry of Health N132 billion.